== THE FULL PICTURE

_The difficulty is real._ More than 70% of mothers experience significant breastfeeding challenges—cracked nipples, pain, latch problems, exhaustion. The gap between the idyllic breastfeeding images and reality can be devastating.

_"Perceived insufficient milk" is the leading reason mothers stop._ About half of mothers cite inadequate supply—but actual supply insufficiency affects only about 5% of women. Most mothers can produce enough milk with proper support. The problem? That support often doesn't exist.

_Hospital practices can undermine success._ Some hospitals supplement without clear medical need—49.8% of supplementation is for "lack of milk" and 35.5% for "crying baby." Only 24.6% of supplementation has documented medical justification. Meanwhile, rigid breastfeeding enforcement has been linked to increased newborn falls from exhausted mothers and, in extreme cases, dangerous dehydration.

_The shame culture is real._ Mothers report feeling judged for supplementing, requesting pacifiers, or asking for nursery help. Some mothers have been denied formula despite requesting it, or pressured to continue exclusive breastfeeding when struggling significantly.

_Baby-Friendly designation may not improve outcomes._ Research published in the Journal of Pediatrics found BFHI didn't have the expected positive impact on breastfeeding rates. A UK review found Baby-Friendly boosts breastfeeding only in baby's first week—not beyond.

_Return to work changes everything._ Pumping at work requires time, private space, equipment, and an employer willing to accommodate. While the PUMP Act now provides legal protections, enforcement is imperfect and many mothers find pumping unsustainable long-term.

